    <div class="mb-10">
      <h1 class="text-2xl font-bold text-blue-700 mb-2">How does useEffect work in React?</h1>
      <div class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-4">Asked by <strong class="text-gray-800">Sakshi Singh</strong> • 2 days ago</div>
      <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        I'm new to React Hooks and trying to understand how useEffect works. Can someone explain with an example
        when it runs and how dependencies work?
      </p>
      <div class="mt-4 flex flex-wrap gap-2">
        <span class="bg-blue-100 text-blue-700 px-3 py-1 rounded-full text-xs">react</span>
        <span class="bg-green-100 text-green-700 px-3 py-1 rounded-full text-xs">javascript</span>
        <span class="bg-purple-100 text-purple-700 px-3 py-1 rounded-full text-xs">hooks</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Answers Section -->
    <div class="mb-10">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4 text-gray-800">Answers</h2>

      <div class="space-y-6">
        <div class="bg-gray-50 p-5 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
          <div class="flex justify-between mb-2">
            <span class="font-semibold text-gray-800">Alex R.</span>
            <span class="text-sm text-green-600">✔ Best Answer</span>
          </div>
          <p class="text-gray-700 text-sm leading-relaxed">
            useEffect lets you perform side effects in function components. It runs after the render. You can
            specify a dependency array so that it only runs when those dependencies change. If you leave it empty,
            it runs once like componentDidMount.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-gray-50 p-5 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
          <div class="flex justify-between mb-2">
            <span class="font-semibold text-gray-800">Ritika Sharma</span>
          </div>
          <p class="text-gray-700 text-sm leading-relaxed">
            Think of useEffect like a watcher. It checks for changes in the variables listed in its dependency array.
            If they change, the function inside useEffect runs again.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

